schemaClasses.description: An order item is a line of an order. It includes the quantity and shipping details of a bought offer.

schemaClasses.name: ViewAction
schemaClasses.description: The act of consuming static visual content.

schemaClasses.name: TattooParlor
schemaClasses.description: A tattoo parlor.

schemaClasses.name: EmployeeRole
schemaClasses.description: A subclass of OrganizationRole used to describe employee relationships.

schemaClasses.name: CompleteDataFeed
schemaClasses.description:
A [[CompleteDataFeed]] is a [[DataFeed]] whose standard representation includes content for every item currently in the feed.

This is the equivalent of Atom's element as defined in Feed Paging and Archiving [RFC 5005](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5005), For example (and as defined for Atom), when using data from a feed that represents a collection of items that varies over time (e.g. "Top Twenty Records") there is no need to have newer entries mixed in alongside older, obsolete entries. By marking this feed as a CompleteDataFeed, old entries can be safely discarded when the feed is refreshed, since we can assume the feed has provided descriptions for all current items.

schemaClasses.name: LearningResource
schemaClasses.description:
The LearningResource type can be used to indicate [[CreativeWork]]s (whether physical or digital) that have a particular and explicit orientation towards learning, education, skill acquisition, and other educational purposes.

[[LearningResource]] is expected to be used as an addition to a primary type such as [[Book]], [[Video]], [[Product]] etc.

[[EducationEvent]] serves a similar purpose for event-like things (e.g. a [[Trip]]). A [[LearningResource]] may be created as a result of an [[EducationEvent]], for example by recording one.

schemaClasses.name: Role
schemaClasses.description: Represents additional information about a relationship or property. For example a Role can be used to say that a 'member' role linking some SportsTeam to a player occurred during a particular time period. Or that a Person's 'actor' role in a Movie was for some particular characterName. Such properties can be attached to a Role entity, which is then associated with the main entities using ordinary properties like 'member' or 'actor'.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/06/introducing-role.html).

schemaClasses.name: ArchiveOrganization
schemaClasses.description: An organization with archival holdings. An organization which keeps and preserves archival material and typically makes it accessible to the public.

schemaClasses.name: CookAction

schemaClasses.name: FilmAction
schemaClasses.description: The act of capturing sound and moving images on film, video, or digitally.

schemaClasses.name: ComicCoverArt

schemaClasses.name: UserPlusOnes

schemaClasses.name: Demand
schemaClasses.description: A demand entity represents the public, not necessarily binding, not necessarily exclusive, announcement by an organization or person to seek a certain type of goods or services. For describing demand using this type, the very same properties used for Offer apply.

schemaClasses.name: MusicComposition

schemaClasses.name: ConfirmAction

schemaClasses.name: PriceComponentTypeEnumeration

schemaClasses.name: EventVenue
schemaClasses.description: An event venue.

schemaClasses.name: ElectronicsStore

schemaClasses.name: EventSeries
schemaClasses.description:
A series of [[Event]]s. Included events can relate with the series using the [[superEvent]] property.

An EventSeries is a collection of events that share some unifying characteristic. For example, "The Olympic Games" is a series, which
is repeated regularly. The "2012 London Olympics" can be presented both as an [[Event]] in the series "Olympic Games", and as an
[[EventSeries]] that included a number of sporting competitions as Events.

The nature of the association between the events in an [[EventSeries]] can vary, but typical examples could
include a thematic event series (e.g. topical meetups or classes), or a series of regular events that share a location, attendee group and/or organizers.

EventSeries has been defined as a kind of Event to make it easy for publishers to use it in an Event context without
worrying about which kinds of series are really event-like enough to call an Event. In general an EventSeries
may seem more Event-like when the period of time is compact and when aspects such as location are fixed, but
it may also sometimes prove useful to describe a longer-term series as an Event.

schemaClasses.name: MobileApplication

Recommendations may be for products or services, or other concrete things, as in the case of a ranked list or product guide. A [[Guide]] may list multiple recommendations for different categories. For example, in a [[Guide]] about which TVs to buy, the author may have several [[Recommendation]]s.

schemaClasses.name: OpinionNewsArticle

schemaClasses.name: MedicalCause
schemaClasses.description: The causative agent(s) that are responsible for the pathophysiologic process that eventually results in a medical condition, symptom or sign. In this schema, unless otherwise specified this is meant to be the proximate cause of the medical condition, symptom or sign. The proximate cause is defined as the causative agent that most directly results in the medical condition, symptom or sign. For example, the HIV virus could be considered a cause of AIDS. Or in a diagnostic context, if a patient fell and sustained a hip fracture and two days later sustained a pulmonary embolism which eventuated in a cardiac arrest, the cause of the cardiac arrest (the proximate cause) would be the pulmonary embolism and not the fall. Medical causes can include cardiovascular, chemical, dermatologic, endocrine, environmental, gastroenterologic, genetic, hematologic, gynecologic, iatrogenic, infectious, musculoskeletal, neurologic, nutritional, obstetric, oncologic, otolaryngologic, pharmacologic, psychiatric, pulmonary, renal, rheumatologic, toxic, traumatic, or urologic causes; medical conditions can be causes as well.

schemaClasses.name: Trip

schemaClasses.description: ProductReturnEnumeration enumerates several kinds of product return policy. Note that this structure may not capture all aspects of the policy.

schemaClasses.name: GameServerStatus
schemaClasses.description: Status of a game server.

schemaClasses.name: WantAction
schemaClasses.description: The act of expressing a desire about the object. An agent wants an object.

schemaClasses.name: EventStatusType
schemaClasses.description: EventStatusType is an enumeration type whose instances represent several states that an Event may be in.

schemaClasses.name: AmusementPark
schemaClasses.description: An amusement park.

schemaClasses.name: LegalService
schemaClasses.description: A LegalService is a business that provides legally-oriented services, advice and representation, e.g. law firms.\n\nAs a [[LocalBusiness]] it can be described as a [[provider]] of one or more [[Service]]\(s).

schemaClasses.name: BloodTest
schemaClasses.description: A medical test performed on a sample of a patient's blood.

schemaClasses.name: DrugCost
schemaClasses.description: The cost per unit of a medical drug. Note that this type is not meant to represent the price in an offer of a drug for sale; see the Offer type for that. This type will typically be used to tag wholesale or average retail cost of a drug, or maximum reimbursable cost. Costs of medical drugs vary widely depending on how and where they are paid for, so while this type captures some of the variables, costs should be used with caution by consumers of this schema's markup.

schemaClasses.name: ShoeStore
schemaClasses.description: A shoe store.

schemaClasses.name: Mosque
schemaClasses.description: A mosque.

schemaClasses.name: DeliveryMethod
schemaClasses.description:
A delivery method is a standardized procedure for transferring the product or service to the destination of fulfillment chosen by the customer. Delivery methods are characterized by the means of transportation used, and by the organization or group that is the contracting party for the sending organization or person.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeDirectDownload
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeFreight
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeMail
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeOwnFleet
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModePickUp
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DHL
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#FederalExpress
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#UPS

schemaClasses.name: Patient
schemaClasses.description: A patient is any person recipient of health care services.

schemaClasses.name: AutoRental
schemaClasses.description: A car rental business.

schemaClasses.name: BrokerageAccount
schemaClasses.description: An account that allows an investor to deposit funds and place investment orders with a licensed broker or brokerage firm.

schemaClasses.name: CableOrSatelliteService
schemaClasses.description: A service which provides access to media programming like TV or radio. Access may be via cable or satellite.

schemaClasses.name: HowToTool
schemaClasses.description: A tool used (but not consumed) when performing instructions for how to achieve a result.

schemaClasses.name: QuoteAction
schemaClasses.description: An agent quotes/estimates/appraises an object/product/service with a price at a location/store.

schemaClasses.name: Artery
schemaClasses.description: A type of blood vessel that specifically carries blood away from the heart.

schemaClasses.name: SurgicalProcedure
schemaClasses.description: A medical procedure involving an incision with instruments; performed for diagnose, or therapeutic purposes.

schemaClasses.name: Specialty
schemaClasses.description: Any branch of a field in which people typically develop specific expertise, usually after significant study, time, and effort.

schemaClasses.name: MedicalGuidelineContraindication
schemaClasses.description: A guideline contraindication that designates a process as harmful and where quality of the data supporting the contraindication is sound.

schemaClasses.name: CategoryCodeSet
schemaClasses.description: A set of Category Code values.

schemaClasses.name: Code
schemaClasses.description: Computer programming source code. Example: Full (compile ready) solutions, code snippet samples, scripts, templates.

schemaClasses.name: Book
schemaClasses.description: A book.

schemaClasses.name: ContactPoint
schemaClasses.description: A contact point—for example, a Customer Complaints department.

schemaClasses.name: DryCleaningOrLaundry
schemaClasses.description: A dry-cleaning business.

schemaClasses.name: TelevisionChannel
schemaClasses.description: A unique instance of a television BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.

schemaClasses.name: WebSite
schemaClasses.description: A WebSite is a set of related web pages and other items typically served from a single web domain and accessible via URLs.

schemaClasses.name: MedicalTherapy
schemaClasses.description: Any medical intervention designed to prevent, treat, and cure human diseases and medical conditions, including both curative and palliative therapies. Medical therapies are typically processes of care relying upon pharmacotherapy, behavioral therapy, supportive therapy (with fluid or nutrition for example), or detoxification (e.g. hemodialysis) aimed at improving or preventing a health condition.

schemaClasses.name: PublicationIssue
schemaClasses.description: A part of a successively published publication such as a periodical or publication volume, often numbered, usually containing a grouping of works such as articles.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/09/schemaorg-support-for-bibliographic_2.html).

schemaClasses.name: OfferItemCondition
schemaClasses.description: A list of possible conditions for the item.

schemaClasses.name: Service
schemaClasses.description: A service provided by an organization, e.g. delivery service, print services, etc.

schemaClasses.name: DigitalDocumentPermission
schemaClasses.description: A permission for a particular person or group to access a particular file.

schemaClasses.name: EventReservation
schemaClasses.description: A reservation for an event like a concert, sporting event, or lecture.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use [[Offer]].

schemaClasses.name: PropertyValue
schemaClasses.description: A property-value pair, e.g. representing a feature of a product or place. Use the 'name' property for the name of the property. If there is an additional human-readable version of the value, put that into the 'description' property.\n\n Always use specific schema.org properties when a) they exist and b) you can populate them. Using PropertyValue as a substitute will typically not trigger the same effect as using the original, specific property.

schemaClasses.name: VitalSign
schemaClasses.description: Vital signs are measures of various physiological functions in order to assess the most basic body functions.

schemaClasses.name: Airline
schemaClasses.description: An organization that provides flights for passengers.

schemaClasses.name: BroadcastService
schemaClasses.description: A delivery service through which content is provided via broadcast over the air or online.

schemaClasses.name: UKNonprofitType
schemaClasses.description: UKNonprofitType: Non-profit organization type originating from the United Kingdom.

schemaClasses.name: LinkRole
schemaClasses.description: A Role that represents a Web link e.g. as expressed via the 'url' property. Its linkRelationship property can indicate URL-based and plain textual link types e.g. those in IANA link registry or others such as 'amphtml'. This structure provides a placeholder where details from HTML's link element can be represented outside of HTML, e.g. in JSON-LD feeds.

schemaClasses.name: PublicationVolume
schemaClasses.description: A part of a successively published publication such as a periodical or multi-volume work, often numbered. It may represent a time span, such as a year.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/09/schemaorg-support-for-bibliographic_2.html).

schemaClasses.name: MedicalTest
schemaClasses.description: Any medical test, typically performed for diagnostic purposes.

schemaClasses.name: NutritionInformation
schemaClasses.description: Nutritional information about the recipe.

schemaClasses.name: TVSeries
schemaClasses.description: CreativeWorkSeries dedicated to TV broadcast and associated online delivery.

schemaClasses.name: TypeAndQuantityNode
schemaClasses.description: A structured value indicating the quantity, unit of measurement, and business function of goods included in a bundle offer.

schemaClasses.name: EducationalOrganization
schemaClasses.description: An educational organization.

schemaClasses.name: Vessel
schemaClasses.description: A component of the human body circulatory system comprised of an intricate network of hollow tubes that transport blood throughout the entire body.

schemaClasses.name: Country
schemaClasses.description: A country.

schemaClasses.name: PawnShop
schemaClasses.description: A shop that will buy, or lend money against the security of, personal possessions.

schemaClasses.name: OfferShippingDetails
schemaClasses.description:
OfferShippingDetails represents information about shipping destinations.

Multiple of these entities can be used to represent different shipping rates for different destinations:

One entity for Alaska/Hawaii. A different one for continental US.A different one for all France.

Multiple of these entities can be used to represent different shipping costs and delivery times.

Two entities that are identical but differ in rate and time:

e.g. Cheaper and slower: $5 in 5-7days
or Fast and expensive: $15 in 1-2 days

schemaClasses.name: BookSeries
schemaClasses.description: A series of books. Included books can be indicated with the hasPart property.

schemaClasses.name: ParentAudience
schemaClasses.description: A set of characteristics describing parents, who can be interested in viewing some content.

schemaClasses.name: EmergencyService
schemaClasses.description: An emergency service, such as a fire station or ER.

schemaClasses.name: MedicalStudyStatus
schemaClasses.description: The status of a medical study. Enumerated type.

schemaClasses.name: Message
schemaClasses.description: A single message from a sender to one or more organizations or people.

schemaClasses.name: DaySpa
schemaClasses.description: A day spa.

schemaClasses.name: ArtGallery
schemaClasses.description: An art gallery.

schemaClasses.name: CityHall
schemaClasses.description: A city hall.

schemaClasses.name: EndorsementRating
schemaClasses.description:
An EndorsementRating is a rating that expresses some level of endorsement, for example inclusion in a "critic's pick" blog, a
"Like" or "+1" on a social network. It can be considered the [[result]] of an [[EndorseAction]] in which the [[object]] of the action is rated positively by
some [[agent]]. As is common elsewhere in schema.org, it is sometimes more useful to describe the results of such an action without explicitly describing the [[Action]].

An [[EndorsementRating]] may be part of a numeric scale or organized system, but this is not required: having an explicit type for indicating a positive,
endorsement rating is particularly useful in the absence of numeric scales as it helps consumers understand that the rating is broadly positive.

schemaClasses.name: MovingCompany
schemaClasses.description: A moving company.

schemaClasses.name: InsuranceAgency
schemaClasses.description: An Insurance agency.

schemaClasses.name: WebPage
schemaClasses.description: A web page. Every web page is implicitly assumed to be declared to be of type WebPage, so the various properties about that webpage, such as breadcrumb may be used. We recommend explicit declaration if these properties are specified, but if they are found outside of an itemscope, they will be assumed to be about the page.

schemaClasses.name: VideoGameClip
schemaClasses.description: A short segment/part of a video game.

schemaClasses.name: TreatmentIndication
schemaClasses.description: An indication for treating an underlying condition, symptom, etc.

schemaClasses.name: Residence
schemaClasses.description: The place where a person lives.

schemaClasses.name: ExerciseGym
schemaClasses.description: A gym.

schemaClasses.name: ComedyEvent
schemaClasses.description: Event type: Comedy event.

schemaClasses.name: Bone
schemaClasses.description: Rigid connective tissue that comprises up the skeletal structure of the human body.

schemaClasses.name: RentalCarReservation
schemaClasses.description: A reservation for a rental car.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations.

schemaClasses.name: SportsActivityLocation
schemaClasses.description: A sports location, such as a playing field.

schemaClasses.name: OrganizationRole
schemaClasses.description: A subclass of Role used to describe roles within organizations.

schemaClasses.name: OfferCatalog
schemaClasses.description: An OfferCatalog is an ItemList that contains related Offers and/or further OfferCatalogs that are offeredBy the same provider.

schemaClasses.name: Play
schemaClasses.description: A play is a form of literature, usually consisting of dialogue between characters, intended for theatrical performance rather than just reading. Note the peformance of a Play would be a [[TheaterEvent]] - the *Play* being the [[workPerformed]].

schemaClasses.name: City
schemaClasses.description: A city or town.

schemaClasses.name: MedicalSpecialty
schemaClasses.description: Any specific branch of medical science or practice. Medical specialities include clinical specialties that pertain to particular organ systems and their respective disease states, as well as allied health specialties. Enumerated type.

schemaClasses.name: Volcano
schemaClasses.description: A volcano, like Fuji san.

schemaClasses.name: ShippingDeliveryTime
schemaClasses.description: ShippingDeliveryTime provides various pieces of information about delivery times for shipping.

schemaClasses.name: RejectAction
schemaClasses.description:
The act of rejecting to/adopting an object.

Related actions:

* [[AcceptAction]]: The antonym of RejectAction.

schemaClasses.name: Property
schemaClasses.description: A property, used to indicate attributes and relationships of some Thing; equivalent to rdf:Property.

schemaClasses.name: MedicalDevicePurpose
schemaClasses.description: Categories of medical devices, organized by the purpose or intended use of the device.

schemaClasses.name: MediaObject
schemaClasses.description: A media object, such as an image, video, or audio object embedded in a web page or a downloadable dataset i.e. DataDownload. Note that a creative work may have many media objects associated with it on the same web page. For example, a page about a single song (MusicRecording) may have a music video (VideoObject), and a high and low bandwidth audio stream (2 AudioObject's).

schemaClasses.name: Notary
schemaClasses.description: A notary.

schemaClasses.name: DrugPregnancyCategory
schemaClasses.description: Categories that represent an assessment of the risk of fetal injury due to a drug or pharmaceutical used as directed by the mother during pregnancy.

schemaClasses.name: MedicalRiskCalculator
schemaClasses.description: A complex mathematical calculation requiring an online calculator, used to assess prognosis. Note: use the url property of Thing to record any URLs for online calculators.

schemaClasses.name: CheckoutPage
schemaClasses.description: Web page type: Checkout page.

schemaClasses.name: BedDetails
schemaClasses.description: An entity holding detailed information about the available bed types, e.g. the quantity of twin beds for a hotel room. For the single case of just one bed of a certain type, you can use bed directly with a text. See also [[BedType]] (under development).

schemaClasses.name: Substance
schemaClasses.description: Any matter of defined composition that has discrete existence, whose origin may be biological, mineral or chemical.

schemaClasses.name: Dentist
schemaClasses.description: A dentist.

schemaClasses.name: NLNonprofitType
schemaClasses.description: NLNonprofitType: Non-profit organization type originating from the Netherlands.

schemaClasses.name: Researcher
schemaClasses.description: Researchers.

schemaClasses.name: ResumeAction
schemaClasses.description: The act of resuming a device or application which was formerly paused (e.g. resume music playback or resume a timer).

schemaClasses.name: AdvertiserContentArticle
schemaClasses.description: An [[Article]] that an external entity has paid to place or to produce to its specifications. Includes [advertorials](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Advertorial), sponsored content, native advertising and other paid content.

schemaClasses.name: MoneyTransfer
schemaClasses.description: The act of transferring money from one place to another place. This may occur electronically or physically.

schemaClasses.name: WholesaleStore
schemaClasses.description: A wholesale store.

schemaClasses.name: Diet
schemaClasses.description: A strategy of regulating the intake of food to achieve or maintain a specific health-related goal.

schemaClasses.name: CreditCard
schemaClasses.description:
A card payment method of a particular brand or name.  Used to mark up a particular payment method and/or the financial product/service that supplies the card account.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#AmericanExpress
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DinersClub
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Discover
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#JCB
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#MasterCard
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#VISA

schemaClasses.name: HowTo
schemaClasses.description: Instructions that explain how to achieve a result by performing a sequence of steps.

schemaClasses.name: MotorcycleRepair
schemaClasses.description: A motorcycle repair shop.

schemaClasses.name: Conversation
schemaClasses.description: One or more messages between organizations or people on a particular topic. Individual messages can be linked to the conversation with isPartOf or hasPart properties.

schemaClasses.name: SelfStorage
schemaClasses.description: A self-storage facility.

schemaClasses.name: WebPageElement
schemaClasses.description: A web page element, like a table or an image.

schemaClasses.name: LibrarySystem
schemaClasses.description: A [[LibrarySystem]] is a collaborative system amongst several libraries.

schemaClasses.name: BankOrCreditUnion
schemaClasses.description: Bank or credit union.

schemaClasses.name: ProductReturnPolicy
schemaClasses.description: A ProductReturnPolicy provides information about product return policies associated with an [[Organization]] or [[Product]].

schemaClasses.name: Guide
schemaClasses.description: [[Guide]] is a page or article that recommend specific products or services, or aspects of a thing for a user to consider. A [[Guide]] may represent a Buying Guide and detail aspects of products or services for a user to consider. A [[Guide]] may represent a Product Guide and recommend specific products or services. A [[Guide]] may represent a Ranked List and recommend specific products or services with ranking.

schemaClasses.name: BookStore
schemaClasses.description: A bookstore.

schemaClasses.name: Blog
schemaClasses.description: A blog.

schemaClasses.name: RentAction
schemaClasses.description: The act of giving money in return for temporary use, but not ownership, of an object such as a vehicle or property. For example, an agent rents a property from a landlord in exchange for a periodic payment.

schemaClasses.name: Distance
schemaClasses.description: Properties that take Distances as values are of the form '<Number> <Length unit of measure>'. E.g., '7 ft'.

schemaClasses.name: PhysicalExam
schemaClasses.description: A type of physical examination of a patient performed by a physician.

schemaClasses.name: MovieClip
schemaClasses.description: A short segment/part of a movie.

schemaClasses.name: MedicalIntangible
schemaClasses.description: A utility class that serves as the umbrella for a number of 'intangible' things in the medical space.

schemaClasses.name: GovernmentOrganization
schemaClasses.description: A governmental organization or agency.

schemaClasses.name: ContactPointOption
schemaClasses.description: Enumerated options related to a ContactPoint.

schemaClasses.name: RadioSeries
schemaClasses.description: CreativeWorkSeries dedicated to radio broadcast and associated online delivery.

schemaClasses.name: LocalBusiness
schemaClasses.description: A particular physical business or branch of an organization. Examples of LocalBusiness include a restaurant, a particular branch of a restaurant chain, a branch of a bank, a medical practice, a club, a bowling alley, etc.

schemaClasses.name: GovernmentPermit
schemaClasses.description: A permit issued by a government agency.

schemaClasses.name: AskPublicNewsArticle
schemaClasses.description: A [[NewsArticle]] expressing an open call by a [[NewsMediaOrganization]] asking the public for input, insights, clarifications, anecdotes, documentation, etc., on an issue, for reporting purposes.

schemaClasses.name: DriveWheelConfigurationValue
schemaClasses.description: A value indicating which roadwheels will receive torque.

schemaClasses.name: Embassy
schemaClasses.description: An embassy.

schemaClasses.name: BroadcastChannel
schemaClasses.description: A unique instance of a BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.

schemaClasses.name: HowToDirection
schemaClasses.description: A direction indicating a single action to do in the instructions for how to achieve a result.

schemaClasses.name: MeetingRoom
schemaClasses.description:
A meeting room, conference room, or conference hall is a room provided for singular events such as business conferences and meetings (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conference_hall).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

schemaClasses.name: MedicalDevice
schemaClasses.description: Any object used in a medical capacity, such as to diagnose or treat a patient.

schemaClasses.name: HinduTemple
schemaClasses.description: A Hindu temple.

schemaClasses.name: DrinkAction
schemaClasses.description: The act of swallowing liquids.

schemaClasses.name: GovernmentBuilding
schemaClasses.description: A government building.

schemaClasses.name: PropertyValueSpecification
schemaClasses.description: A Property value specification.

schemaClasses.name: DModel
schemaClasses.description:
A 3D model represents some kind of 3D content, which may have [[encoding]]s in one or more [[MediaObject]]s. Many 3D formats are available (e.g. see [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category:3D_graphics_file_formats)); specific encoding formats can be represented using the [[encodingFormat]] property applied to the relevant [[MediaObject]]. For the
case of a single file published after Zip compression, the convention of appending '+zip' to the [[encodingFormat]] can be used. Geospatial, AR/VR, artistic/animation, gaming, engineering and scientific content can all be represented using [[3DModel]].

schemaClasses.name: DeactivateAction
schemaClasses.description: The act of stopping or deactivating a device or application (e.g. stopping a timer or turning off a flashlight).

schemaClasses.name: ReplaceAction
schemaClasses.description: The act of editing a recipient by replacing an old object with a new object.

schemaClasses.name: Quiz
schemaClasses.description: Quiz: A test of knowledge, skills and abilities.

schemaClasses.name: CorrectionComment
schemaClasses.description: A [[comment]] that corrects [[CreativeWork]].

schemaClasses.name: Room
schemaClasses.description:
A room is a distinguishable space within a structure, usually separated from other spaces by interior walls. (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Room).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

schemaClasses.name: ItemPage
schemaClasses.description: A page devoted to a single item, such as a particular product or hotel.

schemaClasses.name: Manuscript
schemaClasses.description: A book, document, or piece of music written by hand rather than typed or printed.

schemaClasses.name: URL
schemaClasses.description: Data type: URL.

schemaClasses.name: EducationEvent
schemaClasses.description: Event type: Education event.

schemaClasses.name: TransferAction
schemaClasses.description: The act of transferring/moving (abstract or concrete) animate or inanimate objects from one place to another.

schemaClasses.name: Courthouse
schemaClasses.description: A courthouse.

schemaClasses.name: BedAndBreakfast
schemaClasses.description:
Bed and breakfast.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

schemaClasses.name: Drawing
schemaClasses.description: A picture or diagram made with a pencil, pen, or crayon rather than paint.

schemaClasses.name: DeliveryEvent
schemaClasses.description: An event involving the delivery of an item.

schemaClasses.name: HowToItem
schemaClasses.description: An item used as either a tool or supply when performing the instructions for how to to achieve a result.

schemaClasses.name: Bakery
schemaClasses.description: A bakery.

schemaClasses.name: UserReview
schemaClasses.description: A review created by an end-user (e.g. consumer, purchaser, attendee etc.), in contrast with [[CriticReview]].

schemaClasses.name: PublicToilet
schemaClasses.description: A public toilet is a room or small building containing one or more toilets (and possibly also urinals) which is available for use by the general public, or by customers or employees of certain businesses.

schemaClasses.name: HowToSection
schemaClasses.description: A sub-grouping of steps in the instructions for how to achieve a result (e.g. steps for making a pie crust within a pie recipe).

schemaClasses.name: AdministrativeArea
schemaClasses.description: A geographical region, typically under the jurisdiction of a particular government.

schemaClasses.name: PresentationDigitalDocument
schemaClasses.description: A file containing slides or used for a presentation.

schemaClasses.name: Car
schemaClasses.description: A car is a wheeled, self-powered motor vehicle used for transportation.

schemaClasses.name: VideoObject
schemaClasses.description: A video file.

schemaClasses.name: BusinessAudience
schemaClasses.description: A set of characteristics belonging to businesses, e.g. who compose an item's target audience.

schemaClasses.name: SpeakableSpecification
schemaClasses.description: A SpeakableSpecification indicates (typically via [[xpath]] or [[cssSelector]]) sections of a document that are highlighted as particularly [[speakable]]. Instances of this type are expected to be used primarily as values of the [[speakable]] property.

schemaClasses.name: PriceSpecification
schemaClasses.description: A structured value representing a price or price range. Typically, only the subclasses of this type are used for markup. It is recommended to use [[MonetaryAmount]] to describe independent amounts of money such as a salary, credit card limits, etc.

schemaClasses.name: Mass
schemaClasses.description: Properties that take Mass as values are of the form '<Number> <Mass unit of measure>'. E.g., '7 kg'.

schemaClasses.name: SendAction
schemaClasses.description:
The act of physically/electronically dispatching an object for transfer from an origin to a destination.Related actions:

* [[ReceiveAction]]: The reciprocal of SendAction.
* [[GiveAction]]: Unlike GiveAction, SendAction does not imply the transfer of ownership (e.g. I can send you my laptop, but I'm not necessarily giving it to you).

schemaClasses.name: TouristInformationCenter
schemaClasses.description: A tourist information center.

schemaClasses.name: DanceEvent
schemaClasses.description: Event type: A social dance.

schemaClasses.name: GeoShape
schemaClasses.description: The geographic shape of a place. A GeoShape can be described using several properties whose values are based on latitude/longitude pairs. Either whitespace or commas can be used to separate latitude and longitude; whitespace should be used when writing a list of several such points.

schemaClasses.name: MotorizedBicycle
schemaClasses.description: A motorized bicycle is a bicycle with an attached motor used to power the vehicle, or to assist with pedaling.

schemaClasses.name: ConsumeAction
schemaClasses.description: The act of ingesting information/resources/food.

schemaClasses.name: MedicalRiskFactor
schemaClasses.description: A risk factor is anything that increases a person's likelihood of developing or contracting a disease, medical condition, or complication.

schemaClasses.name: Clip
schemaClasses.description: A short TV or radio program or a segment/part of a program.

schemaClasses.name: OfficeEquipmentStore
schemaClasses.description: An office equipment store.

schemaClasses.name: MusicVideoObject
schemaClasses.description: A music video file.

schemaClasses.name: ItemList
schemaClasses.description: A list of items of any sort—for example, Top 10 Movies About Weathermen, or Top 100 Party Songs. Not to be confused with HTML lists, which are often used only for formatting.

schemaClasses.name: SearchResultsPage
schemaClasses.description: Web page type: Search results page.

schemaClasses.name: CssSelectorType
schemaClasses.description: Text representing a CSS selector.

schemaClasses.name: Photograph
schemaClasses.description: A photograph.

schemaClasses.name: HobbyShop
schemaClasses.description: A store that sells materials useful or necessary for various hobbies.

schemaClasses.name: PostOffice
schemaClasses.description: A post office.

schemaClasses.name: Synagogue
schemaClasses.description: A synagogue.

schemaClasses.name: UserTweets
schemaClasses.description: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

schemaClasses.name: ImagingTest
schemaClasses.description: Any medical imaging modality typically used for diagnostic purposes.

schemaClasses.name: MedicalEntity
schemaClasses.description: The most generic type of entity related to health and the practice of medicine.

schemaClasses.name: Locksmith
schemaClasses.description: A locksmith.

schemaClasses.name: SaleEvent
schemaClasses.description: Event type: Sales event.

schemaClasses.name: CategoryCode
schemaClasses.description: A Category Code.

schemaClasses.name: House
schemaClasses.description: A house is a building or structure that has the ability to be occupied for habitation by humans or other creatures (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/House).

schemaClasses.name: InfectiousAgentClass
schemaClasses.description: Classes of agents or pathogens that transmit infectious diseases. Enumerated type.

schemaClasses.name: FindAction
schemaClasses.description:
The act of finding an object.

Related actions:

* [[SearchAction]]: FindAction is generally lead by a SearchAction, but not necessarily.

schemaClasses.name: Invoice
schemaClasses.description: A statement of the money due for goods or services; a bill.

schemaClasses.name: CheckOutAction
schemaClasses.description:
The act of an agent communicating (service provider, social media, etc) their departure of a previously reserved service (e.g. flight check in) or place (e.g. hotel).

Related actions:

* [[CheckInAction]]: The antonym of CheckOutAction.
* [[DepartAction]]: Unlike DepartAction, CheckOutAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the end of a previously reserved service.
* [[CancelAction]]: Unlike CancelAction, CheckOutAction implies that the agent is informing/confirming the end of a previously reserved service.

schemaClasses.name: DiagnosticLab
schemaClasses.description: A medical laboratory that offers on-site or off-site diagnostic services.

schemaClasses.name: InfectiousDisease
schemaClasses.description: An infectious disease is a clinically evident human disease resulting from the presence of pathogenic microbial agents, like pathogenic viruses, pathogenic bacteria, fungi, protozoa, multicellular parasites, and prions. To be considered an infectious disease, such pathogens are known to be able to cause this disease.

schemaClasses.name: ControlAction
schemaClasses.description: An agent controls a device or application.

schemaClasses.name: HotelRoom
schemaClasses.description:
A hotel room is a single room in a hotel.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

schemaClasses.name: ListenAction
schemaClasses.description: The act of consuming audio content.

schemaClasses.name: GamePlayMode
schemaClasses.description: Indicates whether this game is multi-player, co-op or single-player.

schemaClasses.name: ImageGallery
schemaClasses.description: Web page type: Image gallery page.

schemaClasses.name: Continent
schemaClasses.description: One of the continents (for example, Europe or Africa).

schemaClasses.name: Airport
schemaClasses.description: An airport.

schemaClasses.name: TaxiService
schemaClasses.description: A service for a vehicle for hire with a driver for local travel. Fares are usually calculated based on distance traveled.

schemaClasses.name: DrawAction
schemaClasses.description: The act of producing a visual/graphical representation of an object, typically with a pen/pencil and paper as instruments.

schemaClasses.name: FMRadioChannel
schemaClasses.description: A radio channel that uses FM.

schemaClasses.name: Grant
schemaClasses.description:
A grant, typically financial or otherwise quantifiable, of resources. Typically a [[funder]] sponsors some [[MonetaryAmount]] to an [[Organization]] or [[Person]],
    sometimes not necessarily via a dedicated or long-lived [[Project]], resulting in one or more outputs, or [[fundedItem]]s. For financial sponsorship, indicate the [[funder]] of a [[MonetaryGrant]]. For non-financial support, indicate [[sponsor]] of [[Grant]]s of resources (e.g. office space).

Grants support  activities directed towards some agreed collective goals, often but not always organized as [[Project]]s. Long-lived projects are sometimes sponsored by a variety of grants over time, but it is also common for a project to be associated with a single grant.

The amount of a [[Grant]] is represented using [[amount]] as a [[MonetaryAmount]].

schemaClasses.description:
An [[OfferForLease]] in Schema.org represents an [[Offer]] to lease out something, i.e. an [[Offer]] whose
  [[businessFunction]] is [lease out](http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#LeaseOut.). See [Good Relations](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GoodRelations) for
  background on the underlying concepts.
